quran[28]{c,v,t}:
  69,35,"So he has no intimate<i class=""s"">(friend) </i>here today,"
  69,36,"nor any food except scum,"
  69,37,"which none eats except the wrongdoers.”"
  69,38,"So I swear by what you<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>see"
  69,39,"and what you do not see:"
  69,40,"it is indeed the word{1}of a noble messenger",footnotes:1:The Qur’an.
  69,41,"and in no way is it the word of a poet—little do <span class=""h"">you</span><a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><span class=""h"">believe<sup foot_note=""81362"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>,"
  69,42,"nor is it the speech of a soothsayer—little do you <span class=""h"">remind yourselves<sup foot_note=""81363"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span>."
  69,43,"<i class=""s"">(It is) </i>a bestowal from on high by the Lord of all realms."
  69,44,"And had he falsely attributed some statements to Us,"
  69,45,"We would certainly have seized him strongly{1},",footnotes:1:Literally ‘by the right arm’, which is a metaphor for strength.
  69,46,"then We would certainly have slashed his aorta,"
  69,47,"and in no way could any of you have defended him."
  69,48,"And indeed, it is a reminding for the mindful<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a><i class=""s"">(of God) </i>."
  69,49,"And indeed, We do know that some of you are disbelievers."
  69,50,"And indeed, it is surely a source of grief for the deniers."
  69,51,"And indeed, it is surely the truth of certitude."
  69,52,"So highly exalt the name of your<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>Lord, the Great."
  70,1,"<span class=""h"">An asker asked<sup foot_note=""81365"" class=""qiraat"">1</sup> </span><span class=""h"">about</span>a punishment sure to come"
  70,2,"for the deniers, that none can repel—"
  70,3,"from Allah, Lord of the Ways of Ascent."
  70,4,"Unto Him the angels and the Spirit ascend on a day the duration of which is fifty thousand years."
  70,5,"So be<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>patient with beautiful patience."
  70,6,"Indeed, they see it distant,"
  70,7,"but We see it near—"
  70,8,"on the day when the sky is like molten brass,"
  70,9,"and the mountains are like tufted wool,"
  70,10,"and no intimate<i class=""s"">(friend) </i><span class=""h"">asks{1} </span>his intimate<i class=""s"">(friend) </i>—",footnotes:1:Abu Jaʻfar and Al-Bazzi in one of his narrations read it as: “. . . and no intimate (friend) is asked (about) his intimate (friend) . . .”
